\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C6H12N2O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-[(2-aminopropanoyl)amino]propanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alanylalanine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C6H12N2O3/c1-3(7)5(9)8-4(2)6(10)11/h3-4H,7H2,1-2H3,(H,8,9)(H,10,11)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Greigite-catalyzed CO2 reduction to formate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite and mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent conditions, anoxic, H2-rich, pH 9-11\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-surface electron transfer reduces CO2 to surface-bound formate under vent redox gradients.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Greigite and related Fe-S minerals are established proto-metalloenzyme analogs for CO2 reduction and are specifically cited as catalysts for formate generation in alkaline hydrothermal systems; this is consistent with iron-sulfur world chemistry and vent CO2 fixation frameworks (Wachtershauser, 1990; Russell & Martin, 2004; Barge et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Further hydrothermal reduction of formate to acetate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite and Fe0\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline hydrothermal vent, reducing conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential mineral-catalyzed CO2-derived C1 reduction and C-C coupling yields acetate as a stable reduced carbon product.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report identifies greigite and elemental iron as reductants/catalysts for conversion of CO2-derived intermediates toward acetate in hydrothermal environments, matching Fe-S world and serpentinization-fed carbon fixation concepts (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Russell & Hall, 1997; Barge et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from reduced carbon\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite and greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic subseafloor/vent setting; pyruvate predicted stable by DEW-type hydrothermal models\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-assisted carbon fixation and carbonylation of reduced C1/C2 species produce the alpha-keto acid pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The deep research report identifies pyruvate as a plausible hydrothermal intermediate produced through CO2 reduction/carbonylation and stabilized under hydrothermal PT conditions; magnetite/greigite-mediated carbon fixation is therefore used to connect reduced carbon pools to pyruvate (Amend et al., 2013; Barge et al., 2019; Wachtershauser, 1990).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type formation of acetaldehyde from CO2-derived carbon\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite and pyrite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic hydrothermal setting with FT-type synthesis of aldehydes\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Surface hydrogenation of carbon oxides on iron minerals yields small aldehydes including acetaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report places aldehydes and ketones among products of reducing spark/volcanic and hydrothermal chemistries, and the instruction set explicitly includes FT-type aldehyde production on magnetite in hydrothermal systems. This reaction is used as a literature-consistent connector between vent carbon fixation and Strecker chemistry (McCollom & Seewald, 2007; Wachtershauser, 1990).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Volcanic/cyanosulfidic generation of HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide minerals and TiO2 under UV exposure\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"volcanic plume or evaporitic pool input, strong UV, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical and sulfide-assisted surface chemistry converts simple volcanic carbon/nitrogen feedstocks into cyanide-bearing reduced carbon pools.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report identifies HCN as a key carbon/nitrogen source in volcanic plumes and cyanosulfidic systems, with H2S and UV central to integrated prebiotic networks. Sulfide minerals and UV-photocatalytic surfaces are therefore specified to ground this surface cyanide source (Miller, 1955; Miller, 1958; Patel et al., 2015; Xu et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Formaldimine formation from HCN-derived C1 nitrogen chemistry\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-irradiated shallow pool; anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical hydrolysis/reduction of cyanide-derived C1 species produces methanimine/formaldimine as a reactive imine intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report explicitly highlights formaldimine as a more reactive and pivotal intermediate than HCN in thermodynamic/network analyses for alanine formation, so it is included as a dedicated node and step. The exact prebiotic conversion remains network-level rather than a single canonical experiment, but its inclusion follows the literature emphasis on formaldimine-mediated access to alanine (Das et al., 2019; Rappoport-related RTIP network analyses as summarized in the report).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Classical Strecker synthesis of alanine aminonitrile from acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite and phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"slightly alkaline aqueous pool; nitrile formation faster than hydrolysis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acetaldehyde condenses with ammonia to an imine, then CN- adds to give 2-aminopropanenitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the canonical Strecker route for alanine described explicitly in the report: acetaldehyde + NH3 + HCN gives 2-aminopropanenitrile via imine formation and hydrocyanation. Mineral surfaces are included per instruction and are consistent with concentration/catalysis in evaporitic settings (Strecker, 1850; Miller, 1953; Pizzarello & Shock, 2010).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Formaldimine-mediated assembly of alanine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide minerals and TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-exposed cyanosulfidic flow chemistry, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reactive methanimine/formaldimine participates in C1/C2 coupling with aldehyde/cyanide chemistry to access 2-aminopropanenitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report specifically notes that formaldimine-mediated pathways to alanine are thermodynamically favorable and may be more robust than the classical cyanide-only picture. This reaction captures that literature-supported alternative within the cyanosulfidic surface network (Das et al., 2019; Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic homologation to alanine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide minerals with 