      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"343-373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mixed-valence iron mineral system represented with pyrite/greigite surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent interface, pH 9-11, 24-48 h, mixed Fe2+/Fe3+ redox conditions analogous to green rust\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate forms an imine/iminium with ammonia, followed by mineral-mediated reduction to alanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report identifies reductive amination of pyruvate as the primary hydrothermal route to alanine, especially under alkaline conditions at 70-100 C with mixed-valence iron minerals such as green rust. Because the mandated hydrothermal mineral list excludes green rust, pyrite/greigite are used as the closest permitted Fe redox minerals while explicitly noting the green-rust experimental basis. This is a constrained but literature-grounded representation (Barge et al., 2019; He et al., 2021 as summarized in the report; Russell & Martin, 2004).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyrite-mediated asymmetric photochemical selection to L-alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"natural pyrite surface\", null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"natural pyrite surface under UV illumination\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"surface/mineral interface; stereoselective selection or kinetic enrichment from racemate\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Asymmetric adsorption/photochemistry on mineral surfaces followed by selective persistence and transfer enriches one alanine enantiomer, here assigned to the target L pool.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report discusses mineral-surface origins of chirality and subsequent transfer/amplification, while also noting that pyrite photocatalysis experimentally favored D-alanine rather than L-alanine. Therefore this node is explicitly a gap-bridging, speculative enrichment/selection step required to reach the requested target L-alanine from the racemate. It is justified by the report's broader discussion of kinetic resolution and transfer of stereochemical information in later prebiotic chemistry, while acknowledging the pyrite contradiction (Bonner, 1991; the pyrite ee study summarized in the report; Blackmond, 2010).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Wet-dry peptide formation from alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycling in evaporitic or geothermal pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Dehydrative condensation during drying phases forms peptide bonds, yielding alanine dipeptides/oligopeptides.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report states that alanine participates in wet-dry-cycle peptide synthesis and that clays such as montmorillonite concentrate and orient amino acids for polymerization. This reaction also connects alanine to later biochemical assembly (Lahav et al., 1978; Rodriguez-Garcia et al., 2015; Lambert, 2008).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Kinetic resolution or templated release of L-alanine from alanine-containing peptide pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null, null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"simple peptide/cofactor-assisted kinetic resolution or template effects\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"geothermal cycling, mineral interfaces, selective hydrolysis/ligation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Selective ligation/hydrolysis and kinetic resolution in a peptide pool enrich the L-enantiomer and release L-alanine into solution.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report notes that kinetic resolution via prebiotically plausible transamination/peptide-cofactor chemistry and stereoselective coded synthesis could amplify enantiomeric excess. This reaction is included as a literature-driven bridge from racemic amino acid chemistry to an L-enriched target pool, while remaining explicitly more speculative than the direct synthesis steps (Blackmond, 2010; Plankensteiner et al., 2004; the coded peptide stereoselection studies summarized in the report).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct hydrothermal vent reductive amination\",\n      \"description\": \"CO2 is reduced to formate and then fixed into pyruvate in hydrothermal systems; pyruvate undergoes mineral-mediated reductive amination to alanine, followed by stereochemical enrichment to the L pool.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate to peptide to L-alanine\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal alanine feeds into wet-dry peptide formation, then peptide-based kinetic resolution returns L-alanine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_