ystems, with H2S and UV central to integrated prebiotic networks. Sulfide minerals and UV-photocatalytic surfaces are therefore specified to ground this surface cyanide source (Miller, 1955; Miller, 1958; Patel et al., 2015; Xu et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Formaldimine formation from HCN-derived C1 nitrogen chemistry", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and phosphate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-irradiated shallow pool; anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical hydrolysis/reduction of cyanide-derived C1 species produces methanimine/formaldimine as a reactive imine intermediate.", "reasoning": "The report explicitly highlights formaldimine as a more reactive and pivotal intermediate than HCN in thermodynamic/network analyses for alanine formation, so it is included as a dedicated node and step. The exact prebiotic conversion remains network-level rather than a single canonical experiment, but its inclusion follows the literature emphasis on formaldimine-mediated access to alanine (Das et al., 2019; Rappoport-related RTIP network analyses as summarized in the report)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Classical Strecker synthesis of alanine aminonitrile from acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_003", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite and phosphate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "slightly alkaline aqueous pool; nitrile formation faster than hydrolysis"}, "mechanism": "Acetaldehyde condenses with ammonia to an imine, then CN- adds to give 2-aminopropanenitrile.", "reasoning": "This is the canonical Strecker route for alanine described e