y cycling in evaporitic or geothermal pools"}, "mechanism": "Dehydrative condensation during drying phases forms peptide bonds, yielding alanine dipeptides/oligopeptides.", "reasoning": "The report states that alanine participates in wet-dry-cycle peptide synthesis and that clays such as montmorillonite concentrate and orient amino acids for polymerization. This reaction also connects alanine to later biochemical assembly (Lahav et al., 1978; Rodriguez-Garcia et al., 2015; Lambert, 2008)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Kinetic resolution or templated release of L-alanine from alanine-containing peptide pool", "inputs": ["mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null, null], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "simple peptide/cofactor-assisted kinetic resolution or template effects", "aqueous": "true", "other": "geothermal cycling, mineral interfaces, selective hydrolysis/ligation"}, "mechanism": "Selective ligation/hydrolysis and kinetic resolution in a peptide pool enrich the L-enantiomer and release L-alanine into solution.", "reasoning": "The report notes that kinetic resolution via prebiotically plausible transamination/peptide-cofactor chemistry and stereoselective coded synthesis could amplify enantiomeric excess. This reaction is included as a literature-driven bridge from racemic amino acid chemistry to an L-enriched target pool, while remaining explicitly more speculative than the direct synthesis steps (Blackmond, 2010; Plankensteiner et al., 2004; the coded peptide stereoselection studies summarized in the report)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Direct hydrothermal vent reductive amination", "description": "CO2 is reduced to formate and then fixed into pyruvate in hydrothermal systems; pyruvate undergoes mineral-mediated reductive amination to alanine, followed by stereochemical enrichment to the L pool.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_009", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate to peptide to L-alanine", "description": "Hydrothermal alanine feeds into wet-dry peptide formation, then peptide-based kinetic resolution returns L-alanine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_011", "rxn_013", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_013", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Hydrothermal acetaldehyde plus classical Strecker route", "description": "Vent-generated acetaldehyde combines with surface HCN and ammonia to make alanine aminonitrile, which hydrolyzes to alanine and is then enriched to L-alanine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_010", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_005", "mol_012", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Hydrothermal acetaldehyde to peptide-mediated L-selection", "description": "The acetaldehyde Strecker product is hydrolyzed to racemic alanine, incorporated into peptides by wet-dry cycling, and resolved toward L-alanine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_010", "rxn_013", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Formaldimine-assisted surface alanine aminonitrile formation", "description": "Surface HCN chemistry generates formaldimine, which participates in a literature-supported alternative route to alanine aminonitrile before hydrolysis and chiral enrichment.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_004", "rxn_008", "rxn_010", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_011", "mol_010", "mol_012", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Formaldimine route with peptide amplification", "description": "The formaldimine-mediated aminonitrile branch feeds into racemic alanine, then wet-dry peptide chemistry and kinetic resolution generate L-alanine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_0