ction, and the formaldimine-mediated assembly of alanine aminonitrile is not sufficiently specified mechanistically. The final chiral selection step again contradicts the literature direction on pyrite selectivity.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_004\",\n        \"rxn_005\",\n        \"rxn_006\",\n        \"rxn_008\",\n        \"rxn_012\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Define a more realistic route to formaldimine from C1 nitrogen chemistry\",\n        \"Clarify whether formaldimine assists imine exchange, homologation, or nitrile addition\",\n        \"Avoid claiming direct L-selection on pyrite\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.46,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.42,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.62,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.66,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.86,\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.82,\n        \"rxn_014\": 0.28\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.6,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.69,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.81,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.52,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.64,\n      \"feedback\": \"Adding peptide formation improves the realism of the late-stage prebiotic context, but the same foundational issues remain: weak precursor generation, an uncertain formaldimine branch, and an inadequately supported stereoselective release step. This pathway is conceptually interesting and literature-adjacent, but several reactions need stronger mechanistic grounding.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_004\",\n        \"rxn_005\",\n        \"rxn_006\",\n        \"rxn_008\",\n        \"rxn_014\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Support the formaldimine route with explicit thermodynamic or computationally motivated chemistry\",\n        \"Use peptide formation for stabilization and concentration rather than direct L-alanine production\",\n        \"Differentiate enantioenrichment from absolute enantiospecific synthesis\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.46,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.42,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.5,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.86,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.1\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.47,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.63,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.79,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.38,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.55,\n      \"feedback\": \"This route attempts to map the cyanosulfidic literature onto alanine aminonitrile formation, but it omits a key literature-supported feature: Cu photoredox cycling and more explicit homologation intermediates. As written, the conversion of HCN, H2S, and acetaldehyde directly to alanine aminonitrile is too compressed. The route is directionally consistent with systems chemistry but not sufficiently faithful to the reported mechanism.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_004\",\n        \"rxn_005\",\n        \"rxn_009\",\n        \"rxn_012\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Include UV-driven Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox mediation or state clearly why it is omitted\",\n        \"Break the cyanosulfidic branch into better-defined homologation steps\",\n        \"Do not rely on pyrite for L-alanine selection\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.46,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.42,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.5,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.86,\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.82,\n        \"rxn_014\": 0.28\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.55,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.68,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.83,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.52,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.62,\n      \"feedback\": \"This pathway benefits from adding a plausible wet-dry peptide stage to a compressed cyanosulfidic route. However, the cyanosulfidic chemistry remains oversimplified relative to the literature, and the peptide-based resolution remains speculative. It is a connected and chemically motivated pathway, but not well enough evidenced to be approved.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_004\",\n        \"rxn_005\",\n        \"rxn_009\",\n        \"rxn_014\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Expand the cyanosulfidic chemistry to reflect the literature network more faithfully\",\n        \"Use peptide formation as a side network unless a stereochemical mechanism is explicitly supported\",\n        \"Strengthen precursor generation steps\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.58,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.55,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.46,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.42,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.89,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.86,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.1\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.55,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.78,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.88,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.4,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.63,\n      \"feedback\": \"This is a strong network-integration pathway because it explicitly connects hydrothermal reduced carbon chemistry to surface Strecker chemistry and then to a biochemical target stage. The issue is not topology but chemistry detail: several feeder reactions are weakly specified and the final L-selection is inconsistent with the literature. If evaluated as a route to racemic alanine, it would score much higher.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_002\",\n        \"rxn_003\",\n        \"rxn_004\",\n        \"rxn_005\",\n        \"rxn_012\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Retarget this pathway to racemic alanine or add a literature-supported enantioenrichment module\",\n        \"Improve definition of hydrothermal acetaldehyde and pyruvate 