Fe2+; 24-48 h\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate undergoes imine formation with NH3 followed by mineral-mediated reduction to alanine on layered mixed-valence iron surfaces.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the strongest hydrothermal route in the supplied literature. Experimental chimney simulations showed mixed-valence iron minerals such as green rust generate NH3 and convert pyruvate to alanine under alkaline hydrothermal conditions around 70-100 C; alanine production depends strongly on Fe2+/Fe3+ ratio and pH. Pyrite is included as a coexisting vent mineral surface, but the key catalyst is green rust as specified by the report (Barge et al., 2019; Barge et al., 2022).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Competing ferrous reduction of pyruvate to lactate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe0)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"343-373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"ferrous-dominated mineral assemblage\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline hydrothermal conditions; lower Fe3+ availability shifts chemistry away from amination\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reduction of the alpha-keto group in pyruvate yields the corresponding alpha-hydroxy acid lactate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The research explicitly notes that purely ferrous systems favor reduction of pyruvate to lactate rather than alanine, making this an important competing branch and bottleneck in hydrothermal alanine synthesis (Barge et al., 2019; Barge et al., 2022).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"variable\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"geothermal heating; anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Alpha-keto acid decarboxylation releases CO2 and forms acetaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate decarboxylation to acetaldehyde is included explicitly in the system instructions and is chemically consistent with alpha-keto acid thermal behavior under prebiotic geothermal conditions; it provides a literature-compatible bridge from hydrothermal pyruvate chemistry into surface Strecker chemistry. As a prebiotic link it is reasonable though less directly documented in the supplied report than pyruvate amination itself (Keller et al., 2014; Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface photochemical generation of HCN in volcanic/plume settings\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 photocatalytic surface with sulfur-rich minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-exposed volcanic pools or plume washout; anoxic sulfur-rich environment\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"High-energy photochemical and redox sulfur chemistry converts reduced C/N feedstocks into cyanide-bearing products that accumulate in surface waters.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The supplied report emphasizes localized volcanic plumes and sulfur-rich settings as plausible sources of HCN feeding Strecker and cyanosulfidic networks, though not always via a single mineral-surface elementary step. This reaction is a necessary network connector and is framed as a condensed representation of literature-supported volcanic/photochemical cyanide generation under sulfur-rich surface conditions (Miller, 1957; Parker et al., 2011; Patel et al., 2015; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Formaldehyde-assisted hydrolysis of alanine aminonitrile to racemic alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"clay and phosphate mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycling; nitrile hydrolysis is rate-limiting; formaldehyde facilitation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The aminonitrile hydrolyzes stepwise through amide-like intermediates to alanine; formaldehyde and mineral surfaces facilitate conversion and concentration.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report identifies nitrile hydrolysis as the rate-limiting stage of Strecker synthesis and explicitly notes that it can be facilitated by formaldehyde or mineral catalysts. Clay and phosphate minerals are plausible surface concentrators/catalysts in evaporitic settings. Product is racemic alanine, consistent with the literature (Miller, 1953; Peltzer et al., 1984; Danger et al., 2013).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Classical Strecker assembly of alanine aminonitrile from acetaldehyde, ammonia, and HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral-assisted concentration in aqueous pools\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"slightly alkaline conditions favor imine formation; tidal pools or evaporitic ponds\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acetaldehyde condenses with NH3 to an imine, followed by cyanide addition to generate 2-aminopropanenitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This directly follows the literature-described Strecker route for alanine: acetaldehyde + NH3 -> imine, then hydrocyanation -> 2-aminopropanenitrile. Mineral surfaces are included as required and are plausible concentrators even though the core chemistry is solution-phase. This is one of the best-established prebiotic routes to alanine precursors (Strecker, 1850; Miller, 1953; Pizzarello & Shock, 2010).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Photochemical formation of formaldimine from HCN-derived C1 nitrogen chemistry\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite, ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV-active TiO2 with borate-rich surface environment\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV photochemistry in shallow pools; C1 nitrogen intermediates stabilized by local mineral context\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN-derived photochemical transformations generate reactive C1 imine and carbonyl species, including formaldimine and formaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report highlights recent thermodynamic/network analyses indicating formaldimine as a more reactive and pivotal precursor than HCN in some alanine-forming networks. Because a precise single-step geochemical synthesis was not uniquely specified, this reaction is included as a condensed, literature-motivated connector from HCN photochemistry to formaldimine chemistry and is therefore partially speculative in elementary detail (Das et al., 2019; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Formaldimine-mediated assembly of alanine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV-driven sulfur-rich surface chemistry\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"volcanic or subaerial geothermal pools; network-based C1/C2 coupling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reactive imine C1 chemistry centered on formaldimine couples with C2 carbonyl/cyanide chemistry to furnish alanine aminonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature report specifically notes that RTIP-based reaction network analyses identify formaldimine-mediated alanine pathways as energetically accessible and potentially more robust than classical HCN-only models. This reaction summarizes that alternative precursor logic while preserving alanine aminonitrile as the key experimentally grounded node (Das et al., 2019; Powner et al., 2009).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic photoredox production of alanine aminonitrile from HCN and H2S feedstocks\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV photoredox sulfur mineral environment\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation; cyanosulfidic flow chemistry; copper photoredox is literature