tween hypothesis-generating and experimentally established steps.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.46,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.62,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.82\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.66,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.74,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.8,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.4,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.64,\n      \"feedback\": \"The pathway is directionally consistent with cyanosulfidic systems chemistry, but it omits a key literature feature: copper photoredox catalysis. As written, the direct conversion of HCN, H2S, and acetaldehyde to alanine aminonitrile is too compressed. It is useful as a network branch to aminonitrile formation, but not well enough specified to stand alone as a strong route.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_006\",\n        \"rxn_011\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Include Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox and more explicit homologation intermediates to better match the Sutherland-style network.\",\n        \"Clarify whether acetaldehyde is exogenous or derived upstream within the cyanosulfidic system.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.46,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.62,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.82,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.84,\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.45\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.63,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.73,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.82,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.67,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.64,\n      \"feedback\": \"This extends the cyanosulfidic branch into peptide selection, but both the precursor chemistry and final enantiomer-selection step are incompletely specified relative to the literature. The pathway is a reasonable network hypothesis, yet it remains below approval because the key target-defining steps are not strongly demonstrated.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_006\",\n        \"rxn_011\",\n        \"rxn_013\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Strengthen the cyanosulfidic segment with explicit photoredox catalysts and intermediates.\",\n        \"Support the stereoselection step with a clearer RNA-templated mechanism or downgrade claims to enrichment rather than production.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.87,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.68,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.72,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.82,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.84,\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.45\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.73,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.9,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.95,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.71,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.78,\n      \"feedback\": \"This is the best network-level pathway because it demonstrates the intended hydrothermal to surface to biochemical progression and strong convergence on shared intermediates. Its weaknesses are concentrated in the pyruvate origin simplification and the final L-selective step, which is plausible only as an enrichment/selection process rather than a firmly established direct synthesis of free L-alanine. Topologically and conceptually this is the strongest route, but it still falls slightly short of approval due to limited support for the final stereochemical resolution.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_002\",\n        \"rxn_013\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Retain this as the flagship pathway but explicitly label the final step as enantioenrichment/selection rather than definitive synthesis.\",\n        \"Add a more direct literature-backed bridge between peptide stereoselection and free L-alanine persistence.\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"best_pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n  \"overall_confidence\": 0.74,\n  \"network_feedback\": \"The network is topologically strong and mostly connected, with adequate size, clear hubs, and multiple convergent branches centered on HCN, acetaldehyde, pyruvate, alanine aminonitrile, and racemic alanine. Environmental interconnection is a major strength: hydrothermal pyruvate chemistry feeds surface Strecker chemistry through acetaldehyde, and both hydrothermal and surface branches converge into biochemical peptide/selection modules. The hydrothermal green-rust pyruvate amination logic aligns well with the provided literature, and the explicit avoidance of pyrite-derived D-alanine asymmetry is scientifically appropriate. The largest issues are chemical and literature-related rather than topological. Several reactions are compressed beyond what the literature directly supports, especially hydrothermal pyruvate generation from CO2/formate, surface HCN generation from CO2/NH3/H2S, and the formaldimine branch. Most importantly, the network reaches racemic alanine robustly, but free L-alanine is obtained only through speculative biochemical selection steps. The literature supports racemic alanine formation strongly and L-selective peptide/template effects qualitatively, but not a clean, direct conversion to free L-alanine as represented here. Mineral-agent compliance is mixed: the prompt required explicit mineral agents for every hydrothermal and surface reaction, and while the reaction summaries name catalysts for some hydrothermal steps, the cyanosulfidic branch omits literature-critical copper photoredox catalysis and the evaluation input does not clearly document mineral agents for every relevant reaction. Overall, this is a good integrated prebiotic alanine network, but it is not yet an approved L-alanine network under a strict target-achievement standard.\",\n  \"approved\": false,\n  \"hub_quality\": 0.9,\n  \"convergence_quality\": 0.88\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluations": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "reaction_score