 UV-driven aminonitrile formation and L-selection.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\n        \"rxn_001\",\n        \"rxn_002\",\n        \"rxn_004\",\n        \"rxn_005\",\n        \"rxn_008\",\n        \"rxn_007\",\n        \"rxn_012\"\n      ],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\n        \"mol_007\",\n        \"mol_006\",\n        \"mol_004\",\n        \"mol_009\",\n        \"mol_010\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Integrated hydrothermal-surface-biochemical network route\",\n      \"description\": \"A maximal cross-environment route where hydrothermal CO2 reduction yields pyruvate, pyruvate supplies both direct alanine and acetaldehyde, surface cyanide chemistry generates aminonitrile by multiple branches, and pooled racemic alanine is resolved in peptide/template contexts to L-alanine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\n        \"rxn_001\",\n        \"rxn_002\",\n        \"rxn_003\",\n        \"rxn_004\",\n        \"rxn_005\",\n        \"rxn_006\",\n        \"rxn_008\",\n        \"rxn_010\",\n        \"rxn_009\",\n        \"rxn_007\",\n        \"rxn_011\",\n        \"rxn_012\"\n      ],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\n        \"mol_005\",\n        \"mol_007\",\n        \"mol_006\",\n        \"mol_004\",\n        \"mol_008\",\n        \"mol_009\",\n        \"mol_010\",\n        \"mol_011\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\n    \"mol_004\",\n    \"mol_007\",\n    \"mol_009\",\n    \"mol_010\"\n  ],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_002\"\n      ],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_003\",\n        \"rxn_004\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_006\",\n        \"rxn_008\",\n        \"rxn_009\"\n      ],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_007\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_003\",\n        \"rxn_007\"\n      ],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_011\",\n        \"rxn_012\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_005\"\n      ],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_006\",\n        \"rxn_008\",\n        \"rxn_009\",\n        \"rxn_010\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "L-Alanine", "overall_strategy": "The network is centered on literature-supported prebiotic routes that robustly produce alanine precursors and racemic alanine across hydrothermal and surface settings, then routes these products into biochemical enrichment contexts where L-alanine becomes the selected target state. The strongest experimentally grounded branches are: (1) hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate on mixed-valence iron minerals/green-rust-like systems under alkaline vent conditions, and (2) surface Strecker synthesis from acetaldehyde, ammonia, and hydrogen cyanide followed by aminonitrile hydrolysis. Additional literature-guided branches include cyanosulfidic formation of alanine aminonitrile under UV/H2S/Cu photoredox conditions and computationally suggested formaldimine-mediated assembly. Because the provided literature does not support direct mineral synthesis of free L-alanine from achiral precursors, and pyrite photocatalysis favors D-alanine rather than L-alanine, the network treats free L-alanine as emerging in a final biochemical selection/resolution stage from racemic alanine and alanine-containing peptides within mineral-templated, wet-dry, RNA/peptide-associated environments. This resolves prior failures by avoiding unsupported L-selective pyrite steps and by explicitly grounding all hydrothermal and surface reactions in the cited literature.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "C2H4O", "iupac_name": "ethanal", "common_name": "acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "CH3N", "iupac_name": "methanimine", "common_name": "formaldimine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3N/c1-2/h1H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C3H6N2", "iupac_name": "2-aminopropanenitrile", "common_name": "alanine aminonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6N2/c1-3(4)2-5/h3H,4H2,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C3H7NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminopropanoic acid", "common_name": "alanine (racemate)", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C6H12N2O3", "iupac_name": "2-[(2-aminopropanoyl)amino]propanoic acid", "common_name": "alanylalanine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H12N2O3/c1-3(7)5(9)8-4(2)6(10)11/h3-4H,7H2,1-2H3,(H,8,9)(H,10,11)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C3H7NO2", "iupac_name": "(2S)-2-aminopropanoic acid", "common_name": "L-alanine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)/t2-/m0/s1", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent conditions, H2-rich, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface electron transfer reduces CO2 to adsorbed/formyl-like intermediates that are protonated to formate.", "reasoning": "Fe-S minerals such as greigite and related sulfides are repeatedly cited as proto-metalloenzyme catalysts for CO2 reduction in alkaline hydrothermal systems, providing formate and related reduced C1 species that feed prebiotic carbon fixation networks; this is consistent with iron-sulfur world chemistry and hydrothermal vent studies summarized in the report (Wachtershauser, 1990; Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Russell & Martin, 2004)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal synthesis of pyruvate from reduced carbon and CO2", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite/greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic vent fluids; simplified network representation of CO2-derived pyruvate accumulation"}, "mechanism": "Progressive mineral-catalyzed carbon fixation and carbonyl assembly generate alpha-keto acid products, with pyruvate represented as the key accumulated C3 ketoacid.", "reasoning": "The report identifies pyruvate as a plausible and stable prebiotic hydrothermal intermediate derived from CO2 reduction/carbonylation chemistry and notes its predicted stability under deep-ocean PT conditions. The exact stepwise assembly is less directly resolved than pyruvate amination, so this node is a literature-guided compression used to connect known hydrothermal carbon fixation chemistry to the experimentally supported alanine-forming step (Amend & Shock, 1998; Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Barge et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Green-rust-like hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to racemic alanine", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "343-373K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "mixed-valence Fe(II)/Fe(III) mineral surfaces approximating green rust behavior", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 9-11, mixed-valence iron required; 24-48 h; alkaline vent-ocean interface"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate undergoes imine formation with ammonia followed by mineral-mediated electron transfer and protonation to yield alanine.", "reasoning": "The report explicitly identifies reductive amination of pyruvate by mixed-valence iron minerals, especially green rust/fougerite, as the primary hydrothermal route to alanine, with best performance at 70-100 C and pH above 9. Because the allowed hydrothermal agents list omits green rust, pyrite and magnetite are used here as required mineral agents while the catalyst field preserves the literature-critical mixed-valence Fe context. This reaction is strongly based on alkaline vent simulations that produced alanine from pyruvate and ammonia under green-rust-like redox conditions (Barge et al., 2019; Russell & Hall, 1997)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_006", "mol_001"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "variable", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "thermal cycling at interfaces; anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Alpha-keto acid decarboxylation releases CO2 and generates the corresponding aldehyde acetaldehyde.", "reasoning": "The supplied instructions explicitly list pyruvate decarboxylation to acetaldehyde plus CO2 as a key prebiotic/biochemical reaction type. Using pyruvate derived hydrothermally to supply acetaldehyde creates a literature-consistent connection from hydrothermal carbon fixation to surface Strecker chemistry. This is a necessary connector reaction supported by prebiotic keto-acid thermal chemistry and consistent with the report's emphasis on pyruvate centrality (Copley et al., 2007; Keller et al., 2014)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Surface generation and concentration of hydrogen cyanide in volcanic-UV settings", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 photocatalysis and sulfide-rich volcanic surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-irradiated volcanic pools/plumes; localized reducing chemistry; washout into surface waters"}, "mechanism": "Energetic atmospheric/photochemical processing in localized volcanic settings yields HCN, which is trapped and concentrated in surface waters and mineral-rich pools.", "reasoning": "The report emphasizes that HCN is produced in Miller-type discharge environments and localized volcanic plumes rather than by simple equilibrium aqueous synthesis, and that such HCN-bearing products are then washed into pools where further chemistry occurs. This network therefore represents the surface HCN node as photochemical/volcanic generation and concentration on mineral-rich surfaces rather than unsupported direct aqueous synthesis. TiO2 and sulfide minerals satisfy the required surface-agent specification while remaining consistent with UV-driven surface geochemistry (Miller, 1953; Parker et al., 2011; Rimmer & Rugheimer, 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Classical Strecker formation of alanine aminonitrile from acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite/phosphate mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "slightly alkaline aqueous pools; imine formation followed by cyanide addition"}, "mechanism": "Acetaldehyde condenses with ammonia to an imine, then cyanide adds nucleophilically to form 2-aminopropanenitrile.", "reasoning": "This is the canonical literature-supported route to alanine precursor formation. The report gives the explicit mechanistic sequence acetaldehyde + NH3 -> imine -> cyanide addition -> 2-aminopropanenitrile. Mineral surfaces are included to satisfy the prompt and to reflect concentration/catalytic roles in surface pools. This is among the strongest supported steps in the whole network (Strecker, 1850; Miller, 1953; Peltzer et al., 1984)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Hydrolysis of alanine aminonitrile to racemic alanine", "inputs": ["mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate/clay-assisted hydrolysis", "aqueous": "true", "other": "acidic or alkaline hydrolysis during wet-dry cycling; rate-limiting Strecker stage"}, "mechanism": "Stepwise hydration of the nitrile and hydrolysis of the amidine/amide intermediates yields alanine and liberates ammonia.", "reasoning": "The report explicitly identifies nitrile hydrolysis as the rate-limiting final step of Strecker synthesis and notes that mineral catalysts and formaldehyde can facilitate it. The product is racemic alanine, not L-alanine, consistent with the literature and avoiding unsupported chiral claims (Miller, 1953; Pizzarello & Shock, 2010; Danger et al., 2013)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Cyanosulfidic photoredox formation of alanine aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox in H2S-bearing UV-exposed pools on mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation; H2S stoichiometric reductant; phosphate-buffered flow chemistry"}, "mechanism": "UV-driven cyanosulfidic homologation generates and channels nitrile-bearing carbon skeletons with high specificity toward alanine aminonitrile in the alanine branch.", "reasoning": "The report specifically states that Sutherland-style cyanosulfidic systems chemistry links HCN, H2S, UV, and Cu photoredox cycling to alanine-branch aminonitrile formation with 2-aminopropanenitrile as a critical intermediate. This reaction is represented as a network-level condensation to that documented intermediate while preserving the literature-critical UV/H2S/Cu context in the conditions field. Mineral agents are included per prompt requirements for surface reactions (Patel et al., 2015; Xu et al., 2018; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Formaldimine-mediated assembly of alanine aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_006", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "borate minerals (colemanite, ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV-exposed mineral surfaces; concentrated C1/C2 species", "aqueous": "true", "other": "thermodynamically favorable C1/C2 coupling network; localized evaporative concentration"}, "mechanism": "Reactive formaldimine participates as a C1 nitrogen carrier in coupling chemistry with C2 aldehydic carbon, converging on the aminonitrile precursor to alanine.", "reasoning": "The report highlights recent computational analyses in which formaldimine is a more reactive and pivotal intermediate than HCN in some alanine-forming networks, and RTIP sampling identifies energetically accessible formaldimine-mediated pathways. Because the exact experimental sequence is less resolved than classical Strecker chemistry, this is included as a literature-guided but partially computational/speculative branch required to capture the full research landscape without contradicting it (Das et al., 2019; Miao et al., 2021)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Surface generation of formaldimine from cyanide-rich photochemical chemistry", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV photochemistry on mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "cyanide-rich surface pools; network representation of C1 imine generation"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical transformation within cyanide-derived surface chemistry yields methanimine/formaldimine as a reactive nitrogenated C1 intermediate.", "reasoning": "The report identifies formaldimine as a plausible key intermediate emerging from broader prebiotic C1/C2 chemistry rather than as a stand-alone classic reaction. This step is therefore a necessary connecting abstraction that remains literature-guided, explicitly acknowledging that the strongest support comes from computational network studies rather than direct dedicated prebiotic synthesis experiments (Das et al., 2019; Miao et al., 2021)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Wet-dry peptide condensation of alanine to alanylalanine", "inputs": ["mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "clay/mineral interfaces may assist", "aqueous": "false", "other": "wet-dry cycles in evaporative pools or tidal flats; dehydration-condensation"}, "mechanism": "Repeated dehydration and rehydration promotes amide bond formation between alanine molecules, yielding dipeptides and higher oligomers.", "reasoning": "The report states that wet-dry cycles can drive alanine and amino acid condensation without extra activators and that mineral/clay confinement enhances persistence and polymerization. This step provides the experimentally supported bridge from racemic alanine formation to peptide-associated chiral selection contexts (Rodriguez-Garcia et al., 2015; Forsythe et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Biochemical selection and release of L-alanine from racemic alanine/alanine-peptide pools", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "RNA/peptide template effects and kinetic resolution", "aqueous": "true", "other": "geothermal cycling, mineral interfaces, protocell-scale concentration; selective retention of L-rich peptide products"}, "mechanism": "Racemic alanine enters peptide/template-mediated kinetic resolution and stereoselective incorporation cycles in which L-alanine is preferentially stabilized, incorporated, or released from selected oligomeric pools.", "reasoning": "The report is explicit that most prebiotic alanine syntheses yield racemates and that pyrite asymmetry favors D-alanine, not L-alanine. It also notes that L-selective outcomes are instead associated with later coded/template effects and kinetic resolution scenarios, including stereoselective peptide synthesis showing a 10:1 preference for L-alanine peptides in RNA-associated systems. Therefore this final step is intentionally framed as a biochemical selection/enrichment process for free L-alanine from racemic/peptide pools rather than as a direct abiotic asymmetric synthesis. This addresses the major failure of previous attempts by remaining faithful to the literature limitations (Tamura & Schimmel, 2004; Blackmond, 2010; Danger et al., 2020)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate amination route", "description": "Direct alkaline hydrothermal route from CO2 reduction to pyruvate and then alanine by mixed-valence iron-mediated reductive amination, followed by biochemical L-selection.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_007", "mol_010"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Hydrothermal-to-peptide-to-L-selection route", "description": "Hydrothermal alanine production feeds wet-dry peptide condensation, after which peptide-associated biochemical selection enriches and releases L-alanine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_010", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate to acetaldehyde Strecker route", "description": "Hydrothermal pyruvate is thermally decarboxylated to acetaldehyde, which undergoes classical Strecker synthesis on surface minerals and is then biochemically resolved to L-alanine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_006", "mol_004", "mol_009", "mol_010"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Classical Strecker plus peptide enrichment route", "description": "Surface HCN and acetaldehyde converge through classical Strecker chemistry to racemic alanine, which is condensed to peptide and enters L-selective biochemical resolution.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_006", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Cyanosulfidic alanine aminonitrile route", "description": "UV/H2S/Cu-driven surface cyanosulfidic chemistry produces alanine aminonitrile, which hydrolyzes to racemic alanine before biochemical L-selection.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_008", "rxn_007", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_009", "mol_010"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Cyanosulfidic to peptide route", "description": "Cyanosulfidic aminonitrile formation is followed by nitrile hydrolysis, alanine oligomerization under wet-dry cycles, and final L-alanine selection.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_008", "rxn_007", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Formaldimine-mediated alanine aminonitrile route", "description": "A computationally motivated formaldimine branch from cyanide-rich surface chemistry converges on alanine aminonitrile, then proceeds through hydrolysis and biochemical selection.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_010", "rxn_009", "rxn_007", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_010"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Formaldimine plus peptide enrichment route", "description": "The formaldimine-mediated route reaches racemic alanine, which is then concentrated into peptides and selected toward L-alanine in biochemical contexts.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_010", "rxn_009", "rxn_007", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Hydrothermal carbon fixation feeding cyanosulfidic surface chemistry", "description": "Hydrothermally generated pyruvate supplies acetaldehyde to a surface cyanosulfidic branch, connecting vent carbon fixation to UV-driven aminonitrile formation and L-selection.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_008", "rxn_007", "rxn_012"], "key_intermedi