entally. Generating formaldimine directly from HCN and then coupling it to acetaldehyde and cyanide is plausible in a broad network sense, yet this branch is more speculative than the Strecker and hydrothermal amination branches. The final L-alanine step is again the weakest point.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_010\",\n        \"rxn_009\",\n        \"rxn_012\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Mark the formaldimine branch as explicitly computationally supported but experimentally limited.\",\n        \"Add missing precursor chemistry for formaldimine formation instead of deriving it too directly from HCN alone.\",\n        \"Do not treat this branch as a primary route to L-alanine without further stereochemical evidence.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.58,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.72,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.9,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.82,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.46\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.68,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.77,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.86,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.7,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.7,\n      \"feedback\": \"This route improves on P7 by incorporating a plausible peptide-concentration stage, but the core formaldimine chemistry remains less secure than the classical Strecker branch. It is a useful auxiliary pathway for network redundancy, not the strongest literature-backed route. The specific production of L-alanine is still insufficiently demonstrated.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_010\",\n        \"rxn_009\",\n        \"rxn_012\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Treat formaldimine as a secondary or exploratory branch rather than a central route.\",\n        \"Strengthen the mechanistic basis of formaldimine generation in surface settings.\",\n        \"Use peptide-associated selection as enrichment rather than direct conversion to pure L-alanine.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.84,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.63,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.57,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.62,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.81,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.9,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.46\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.69,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.78,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.9,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.7,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.73,\n      \"feedback\": \"This integrated route succeeds conceptually at linking hydrothermal carbon fixation to surface photochemistry and then to biochemical selection. That is a real strength of the network design. However, some of the cross-environment connectors are chemically weaker than the central surface or hydrothermal branches, especially pyruvate generation, pyruvate decarboxylation assignment, and the final L-selection step.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_002\",\n        \"rxn_004\",\n        \"rxn_005\",\n        \"rxn_012\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Improve the handoff between hydrothermal and surface chemistries with better-supported transported intermediates.\",\n        \"Use more direct literature-supported surface sources for acetaldehyde and HCN.\",\n        \"Clarify whether the final stage is chiral enrichment, kinetic resolution, or true asymmetric synthesis.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.84,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.63,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.9,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.57,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.62,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.9,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.9,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.81,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.72,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.58,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.82,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.46\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.74,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.9,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.94,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.74,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.79,\n      \"feedback\": \"This is the strongest network-level pathway because it captures the intended synthesis story: hydrothermal carbon fixation and pyruvate chemistry, surface Strecker/cyanosulfidic diversification, and biochemical concentration/polymerization. It is topologically robust and broadly literature-aligned. Still, it narrowly misses approval because the final L-alanine step is not convincingly established, and several compressed or speculative connector steps reduce strict chemical confidence.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_002\",\n        \"rxn_004\",\n        \"rxn_005\",\n        \"rxn_010\",\n        \"rxn_012\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Replace or weaken the claim of direct L-alanine production and instead present the endpoint as enantioenriched alanine or a proto-biochemical selection state.\",\n        \"Add explicit H2S/Cu photoredox details and intermediates to the cyanosulfidic branch.\",\n        \"Clarify and better support the origin of pyruvate and acetaldehyde with literature-consistent chemistry.\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"best_pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n  \"overall_confidence\": 0.78,\n  \"network_feedback\": \"The network is well designed topologically and shows strong integration across hydrothermal, surface, and biochemical contexts. It contains adequate molecule and reaction counts, multiple hubs, clear convergence at pyruvate, alanine aminonitrile, and racemic alanine, and no obvious isolated subgraphs. Literature alignment is generally good for the major branches: hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine is well matched to mixed-valence iron/green-rust literature, and the Strecker branch from acetaldehyde to alanine aminonitrile to racemic alanine is strongly supported. The network also appropriately avoids claimi